                     <interp inst="def3-565-18730818" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">MARY ANN CASTLE</hi> (50)</persName> 
                  <persName id="def4-565-18730818" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def4-565-18730818" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def4-565-18730818" type="age" value="33"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def4-565-18730818" type="surname" value="HOWE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def4-565-18730818" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN HOWE</hi> (33)</persName>, <persName id="def5-565-18730818" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def5-565-18730818" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def5-565-18730818" type="age" value="24"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def5-565-18730818" type="surname" value="CASTLE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def5-565-18730818" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GEORGE CASTLE</hi> (24)</persName>, and <persName id="def6-565-18730818" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def6-565-18730818" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def6-565-18730818" type="age" value="39"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def6-565-18730818" type="surname" value="WITHAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def6-565-18730818" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN WITHAM</hi> (39)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18730818-565-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18730818-565-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18730818-565-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>, Stealing 1 ton of beeswax, the property of <persName id="t18730818-name-623" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-623" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-623" type="surname" value="FIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-623" type="given" value="JOHN KINGSFORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-623" type="occupation" value="wax bleacher"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18730818-565-offence-1 t18730818-name-623"></join>John Kingsford Field</persName> and others, the masters of Ralph. <hi rend="italic">Second Count</hi>—Receiving the same.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi>. Q.C., <hi rend="italic">with</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. STRAIGHT</hi>, <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution</hi>; <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. F. H. LEWIS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">CROOME</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">appeared for Mary Ann Castle</hi>, <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WARNER SLEIGH</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">for Howe</hi>, <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. MONTAGU WILLIAMS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">for George Castle, and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LYON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">for Scott and Witham.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-624" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-624" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-624" type="surname" value="FIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-624" type="given" value="JOHN KINGSFORD"></interp>JOHN KINGSFORD FIELD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a member of the firm of J. C. &amp; T. Field, of Upper Marsh, Lambeth, wax bleachers—we have another business in the name Cowan &amp; Co., in Moorgate Street—at the time he Was taken, Ralph had been in our employ as a labourer about six years, at Upper Marsh—I did hot know any of the other prisoners—in April this year, three blocks of yellow wax were shown to me by my foreman, Brockwell—in the preceding January, I had executed an order for Messrs. Clark, for shipment of ten tons of wax of a particular kind; the blocks were white and of a special shape—in executing these orders there was necessarily a surplus—that order would be executed at Upper Marsh, and such surplus blocks as remained would be kept on the premises to be worked up again in the next quantity—ten tons of yellow wax were supplied to Messrs. Clark, and I had no complaint of any deficiency—I caused inquiries to be</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180188"></xptr>
               <p>made in April, and came in communication with King, who carries on business in Union Street, Southwark; and about the same time I saw some wax in a bag at my premises at Moorgate Street, broken up—I put two of the blocks together, and am prepared to swear that it was my make and my property—it was not in a state in which I should have sold it—I commu<lb></lb>nicated with the police at Scotland Yard, and obtained the services of Sergeant Croome—I went with him on 18th April to King's premises, and asked him to show me about 3 cwt. of wax; he showed me both white and yellow wax, and I took samples of it on a subsequent occasion—I can swear to 3 cwt. of wax as our manufacture, but I cannot swear we had not sold it, although the white wax I can swear was stolen—the yellow wax was finished, but the white wax was unfinished—King showed me two blocks, about 25 lbs. each, of unfinished wax, besides the 3 cwt. of yellow—I suppose the yellow to be mine as well—in consequence of what King said, I went to Jewell's premises in Gibson Street, Waterloo Road—he is a marine store dealer—I had a prolonged conversation with him, in conse<lb></lb>quence of which I went, on Friday afternoon, to Mrs. Castle's premises, a marine store dealer's, of Union Street, Lambeth Walk, about ten minutes walk from Jewell's—I said "My name is Field, and this is Sergeant Croome of the Detective Force; I have come here in consequence of what I have been told by Mr. Jewell, who tells me that on various occasions he has purchased wax of your son, the wax so purchased is my property, and has been stolen from me, and I have called to ask you what account you can give me of it" (I ought to have mentioned that in the first instance I had asked for George Castle, but his mother said that he was not at home)—she said "I know nothing about the wax; I never had any on my premises, and I am sure my son has not, I don't even know what beeswax looks like; does it look like grease or tallow?"—I said "When will your son return"—she said that it was uncertain, as he was frequently away for days together, and it was quite possible he was in Yorkshire—I said I wished very much to see him—she said "I promise that he shall call on you directly he returns, and if I hear from him before he returns, I will let you know where he is"—I had brought some papers from Jewell's, and I said "I have his receipts which Jewell holds, which he says are in your son's handwriting, for money received for beeswax; is that your son's writing?"—she said "It is like it"—she said "You may, if you please, search the house;" 'that her son in addition to helping her in the business did business on his own account—I then left—next day I went again, but I, had received four other pieces of paper from Jewell—I am not sure whether I had seen Jewell before I went to Castle's house again, but it is quite likely—I merely inquired whether George Castle was there, but did not find him—that was Saturday—I saw Jewell on the Monday, and gave him some information about George Castle, and on that Monday evening George Castle came to me at my office in Lambeth Marsh—I said "Mr. Jewell has given your name to me as the seller of a large quantity of wax"—he said "I have sold wax to Jewell on many occasions, and I can give the receipts of the parties from whom I purchased it"—I asked him where the receipts were—he said "At my house"—I said "I am willing to go with you and see them at once"—I walked with him to his house, and a search was made—two pieces of paper were shown to me—one was a receipt in the name of Howe, of Clapham Road, and another in the name of Woolf, but no address—a statement was made that Woolf resided in the neighbourhood</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180189"></xptr>
               <p>of Spitalfields—I called Castle's attention to the fact that both the receipts related to sales in 1872, and said "Surely the blocks of wax I have seen were not manufactured till 1873, and therefore these receipts can by no possibility apply to them"—he said "I have many other receipts, but they are probably at my mother's house, from where I have only just removed"—this was at his private house, two or three minutes' walk from his mother's—he said "I have made no recent sale to Jewell"—I then went with him to his mother's house, and searched there, but no receipts were found—I then went back to his house—Croome took the particulars of the two receipts, and we left—Castle said "I will call on you on Wednesday"—he did come on the Wednesday, and said "I have been endeavouring to find the parties whose receipts I have shown you, bat I have been unsuccessful"—I told him that Croome had been trying to find Howe, and no such person could be found in the neighbourhood—I don't remember that he made any remark to that—he said he was in the habit of doing business with persons whose names and addresses he did not know—he said "I have bought wax from such parties, and I shall, no doubt, come across them in the course of business shortly, and will get their names and addresses and let you have them, and I will call upon you again next Monday"—I said "Castle, this is an attempt to throw dust in our eyes, and you may call again if you please"—that was Wednesday evening, 23rd April—I saw nothing more of him till the 3rd June, when he was in custody—these (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) are the receipts handed to me by Jewell, which I showed to Mrs. Castle, some of them have no dates—they show a total of 5 cwt. 3 qrs. 2 lbs.—the prices are; 9 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>. 10 1/2 d., and 13<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. per pound—the yellow wax I saw at King's was worth from 15<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. to 18<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a pound, and the white wax from 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 11<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. to 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a pound—I afterwards went to the premises of Johnson &amp; Co., Bishopsgate Street, and saw seven blocks of white wax, representing 2 cwt.—I indentified it as my manufacture—four blocks were saleable and in a finished condition, and three blocks; were unfinished—I afterwards went to Mr. Edwards, the doll maker, in Waterloo Road—he showed me some papers, and I showed him a sample of wax—I did not see any of my wax there; it had been used—I received a communication from a person named Rumble, which I communi<lb></lb>cated to Croome with certain instructions, and he came back to me and brought two pieces <hi rend="italic">of</hi> yellow wax, each weighing six or seven pounds, which I identified—it was in an unfinished state and not as it would be sold—it was worth about 18<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a pound—about the same time I received information from a person named Gadsden, and went to the place of Mr. Williams, 108, Minories, where I saw the witness Addis—I had a conversation with him, in eousequence of which I went to Howe's shop in Cambridge Heath Road, on 28th April—Croome spoke first; he said "I was here a day or two since, purchasing wax, and on my return I found that you charged me less than you should have charged"—Howe rectified the amount, and Croome paid him some money—Croome then said "This is Mr. Field, and he has come about the wax that I purchased"—I said "I am Mr. Field, of Lambeth. I have been robbed of this wax to a very large extent, and this is an officer from Scotland Yard who purchased some wax from you that I know to be mine, in a state in which it would not be sold, I must ask you to tell me from whom you bought it"—he said "I bought it from a man, whose name I do not know, from a traveller who comes round to me every Thursday, and with whom I have done business for some time"—I said "You must</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180190"></xptr>
               <p>know his name and address"—he said "I know neither"—I said "Do you buy goods without getting a bill or receipt?"—he said "No, no doubt I have one somewhere"—he searched, and produced a bill from which the printed head had been torn off, and the writing was so obscure that it could not be deciphered whether it was wax or not—I said that he had made a mistake in giving me that—I still pressed him for the name and address—he said he would ask the man when he called again—on 30th April I called again, leaving Thursday between—I said to Howe "I have called again about that wax, and hope you are in a position to give me the address of the person of whom you bought it"—he said "Yes," and he gave me a receipt in the name of Haywood on one of his own bill-heads—I said "This is no address"—he said "The seller declines to give his address"—I then produced some samples I received from Mr. Gadsden, and said "I am informed you have offered wax to this sample, for sale to the amount of 2 cwt."—he said "I have not'—he was asked that question several times, and repeated the same answer—I can't say whether the samples I showed him were my manu<lb></lb>facture, because they Were so small—Croome mentioned Castle's name amongst several others, as persons from whom he might have bought the wax—he said "No," to 'every name that was mentioned, including Castle—Ralph's name was not mentioned—on Tuesday, 3rd June", my manager, ‘Mr. Walker, brought Witham to me—I made no inducement to Witham, but I had offered a reward by placards—I did not promise not to prosecute him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LYON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you make him any promise in words? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I told him any information he gave me, would not be forgotten—I dis<lb></lb>tinctly suggested to him that he should be a witness—(<hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LYON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">contended that Witham's statement under these circumstances was inadmissible, as a hope of reward was held out id him.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">THE COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">considered that the evidence could not be excluded, as Without was not then under charge, and no promise or threat was made to him.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. STRAIGHT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What did Witham say? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He said "I come to you consequent on feeling regret that so many innocent men should be thrown out of employ"—I had discharged some of my men—I had closed one department of the premises at Upper Marsh—he said • I have offered wax by Castle's instructions to three persons, one is Mr. Hale, of Lambeth Road, and Mr. Steane, of Lambeth Walk, and to an oilman in Union Street, whose name I have forgotten, but I did not succeed in selling any"—he also said "It is within my knowledge that this robbery has gone on for two years and a half, and to the extent of about 3 cwt. a week on an average"—I said "Will you give me any further information?—he said "I must have time to consider of it"—I think he said he wanted twenty-four hours, on some hours—he left, promising to see me at the railway station next morning—he did not see me, because I gave instructions for his apprehen<lb></lb>sion—I have a traveller in my employ named Soames, who in April showed me some wax he had purchased for me—I examined it and identified it as my manufacture—it was white wax finished, and was worth 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SLEIGH</hi>. I am not prepared to prove that Howe did not buy any large quantities of wax—the wax sold by Howe at 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. was sold at a fair price—there are three wax bleachers in the metropolis—I employ the same method as they do, and a method of my own in addition, that leaves a small grain oh the surface which, to a practical eye, is unmig<lb></lb>taxable;</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180191"></xptr>
               <p>but Howe possessed only yellow wax and no bleached wax, to my knowledge—I identify the wax Howe had by its peculiar appearance, and it also fitted into my tins—I swear to my own manufacture; it is my positive and absolute oath—the samples are about as big as walnuts; they are for the purpose of tradesmen judging of the quality—I declined to identify these samples on account of their smallness—samples are generally double that size, you seldom see a piece so small as this—Mr. Gadsden gave this to me—Howe had no idea that Croome was a detective till I said so—Hove was not open in his answers, quite the reverse—he represented the invoice of some oil as the invoice of wax—he said that the man had been there on Thursday and given the name of Haywood, and refused his address—he keeps am oil and colour shop, not a marine store dealer's—I should not have sold this wax in this state; it is competent to anybody to buy, but we don't sell goods in am unfinished state—I do not say that nobody ought to have bought it—I have always denied that—James King has bought a good deal, and Jewell also—John Edwards purchased a large quantity of my wax from King—the is not present—80 lbs. of my wax was purchased by Mr. Sundell, but it was not found there; he had none left—Sundell and Edwards purchased pieces in a finished state—I told Howe that unless he told me how he came in possession of my property I must find out for myself—he knew at that time that Croome was a detective—MESSRS. Johnson are a highly respectable firm—I buy wax largely for the purpose of making up, and I may purchase wax in the market—I very seldom buy wax of my own unfinished—Rumble is my witness—he has been paid money by me in the course of this case—I can't tell you how much—none of it has passed through my hands—he is a painter—I heard it stated at the Police Court that he is a convicted thief—I have given Sergeant Croome money to be expended amongst the witnesses for their travelling expenses to the different Mice Courts—I believe any direct money paid has been paid by our foreman, Thomas Brock well—I saw no wax in Howe's shop—I have heard that it was in the window, exposed for sale, and sold over the counter.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> I heard Rumble examined at the Police Court, and then knew for the first time that he had been convicted, and that after his con<lb></lb>viction he was taken back—I found that Gregory, Penny &amp; Co. had an order from King for wax, but it had not been delivered—the receipt that Howe showed me, with the corner torn off, was for paraffin oil—I did not notice that on the first occasion, because I could not read it—Haywood's receipt represented 28 lbs. of wax—what I received from Addis was a sample of the 2 cwt. he had been asked to sell.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-625" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-625" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-625" type="surname" value="BROCKWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-625" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS BROCKWELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am Mr. Field's foreman, at Tipper Marsh, where the wax bleaching goes on—Ralph was a labourer there—I remember a package being brought from the City premises—I found in it three blocks of yellow wax, similar to those I had manufactured for Clark &amp; Sons in January—I identified a portion of it as sample blocks of that manufacture the remainder of it consisted of oblong blocks of yellow wax in pieces, which I also identify as Messrs. Field's manufacture—I went to King's premises, and saw two blocks of semi-refined wax there, which I identified as Messrs. Field's—it was wax which is not sold by itself, except for the purpose of being mixed with other wax—I also saw, in King's bedroom, about 2 cwt. of refined yellow wax, which I identify as our manufacture—I then went to the landing, and saw four boxes of refined yellow wax, bleached</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180192"></xptr>
               <p>and finished, in condition for sale, which I identified as Mr. Fields manu<lb></lb>facture—I also found a bag there with two sorts of wax in it, mixed up in pieces—that was our manufacture also—I sent to Messrs. Johnson &amp; Sons' some wax of Mr. Field's manufacture, and noticed that two blocks of it were not finished for sale—as to the second lot supplied to Clark, 10 tons of it were made in earthenware vessels—I identify it by the shape of the vessels in which it is made—the former parcel was made in tin vessels—Rumble was ultimately brought to me—his name was mentioned, and I remember his coming to the premises about 24th or 25th April—nine men were brought out altogether, and Ralph amongst them—Humble pointed out Ralph the moment he saw him—on 30th May I went to Messrs. Middleton's premises in St. George's-in-the-East, and was shown some wax there—I had with me a portion of wax that Croome gave me, which had been purchased at Howe's—part of what I saw at Middleton's was in an unfinished state—a portion of that which Croome gave me was unfinished, and both were part and parcel of the same material.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. W. SLEIGH</hi>. I saw some wax in pieces, in a bag, at King's; some of them were as large as the palm of your hand, some larger, and some smaller—I can't say whose manufacture this piece produced is, because it is in such a dirty condition—I don't know that I could recognise it if it was clean, but if it was white wax, and a little larger, I could; if the pieces were clean, it is very likely I might pick out a great portion of them—I think I could recognise this piece without any difficulty, because no one manufactures it in the same way as we do—I know it by the beautiful was in which it is got up; our wax is, I believe, got up better than anyone else's—I don't think it is more difficult to identify white wax than yellow, if you give me a piece of the proper size.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. M. WILLIAMS</hi>. Middleton's looked like an oil-shop when I was there—I should think they are respectable—the wax I saw brought there was about 50 lbs.; one block was in an unfinished state<lb></lb>Johnson &amp; Co. are tallow chandlers, I think—the blocks they brought were not all unfinished; my two were—I don't know Mr. Williams, of the Minories—I don't know how much money altogether has been given to witnesses in this case—I have paid them about 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a day, for their loss of time in attending at the Police Court, but only to four or five, the others were too respectable—I paid Mrs. Denman, Mrs. Booth, and Rumble; that is about all—I can't say how much I gave Mrs. Dennis; I have kept no account—I paid the money out of my own pocket first—I paid her 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., or it may have been a trifle more—it was at the rate of 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a day, and sometimes a little more—the firm have repaid me, but I can't tell you off hand what I charged them for Mrs. Dennis—I <hi rend="italic">drawed</hi> it from Mr. Oliver, the cashier—I have only paid Mrs. Booth 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; and I daresay Rumble has had the same as Mrs. Dennis, two sovereigns—I have seen Mrs. Frances—I have not paid her a penny—I don't know of anyone else distributing the money of the firm—MRS. Simons has had about 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. from me, that was for her and her son; Mrs. Cook was all in the same lot; that includes the lot—I <hi rend="italic">lumped</hi> them all together—I know of several men going into Horsemonger Land Gaol who have been in our employment, and are out of employment through this unfortunate job—I don't know that they went to ask any of the prisoners to give evidence—I don't know of Baker going into Horsemonger Lane Gaol—I never saw him there—I did not wait outside—I know he started to</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180193"></xptr>
               <p>go, he did not go by my authority—he asked me if he should, and I said he must take the responsibility on himself—I don't think he is here.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> Baker was in Mr. Field's employment in the department which is closed—whatever he did or said at Horsemonger Lane Gaol he had no authority whatever from me for—Dennis, Cook, Rumble, and Simons are all witnesses here—Mrs. Cook is Dennis's mother—whatever money I paid applied to the whole family—I paid them nothing except for attend<lb></lb>ance at the Police Court—Dennis only worked for the two Castles, according to her evidence, and Rumble also—Mrs. Simons resides in the neighbour<lb></lb>hood—I know nothing about giving Mrs. Frances 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for a new bonnet—I did not give her money for her <hi rend="italic">mashed</hi> window after she gave her evidence—her window was <hi rend="italic">smashed</hi>—when I used the expression "pieces," that applies to the 50 lbs. of wax in the bag—they offered me a better oppor<lb></lb>tunity of judging than the pieces I have seen to-day.</p>
               <p>J. K. <hi rend="smallCaps">FIELD</hi> (<hi rend="italic">re-called</hi>).</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. MONTAGU WILLIAMS</hi>. King was not a customer of mine at Lambeth Marsh—he was a customer of Ogilvie &amp; Co., whose partner I am—he was not a customer for wax, but for candles and night-lights—he produced the receipts from Jewell—he paid 15<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., 18<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and 20<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a pound—King occupies a good position—Johnson &amp; Co. are unimpeachable; they bought some of this wax in an unsaleable state—the Edwards's are perfectly respectable; they are customers of mine for wax—Williams is undoubtedly a respectable man—he did not buy some of the wax—Addis if in William's employ, but Williams had nothing to do with the wax—the Middletons are highly respectable—they had not dealt with me before—the wax was in a state in which we do not sell it; it was in a state in which I would not send it out—when I first went to Jewell's, I told him it would be the worse for him if he did not tell me of whom he bought the wax, and he told me he got all of it from the Castles—I have endeavoured to find Jewell, but have not been successful—George Castle's is a private house; we did not search it or his mother's house—Mrs. Castle offered to allow us to search.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> I made inquiries of Edwards, Johnson, &amp; Co. and Middle<lb></lb>ton, and they told me satisfactorily how they obtained the wax.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-626" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-626" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-626" type="surname" value="BINGHAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-626" type="given" value="CHARLES COLLYER"></interp>CHARLES COLLYER BINGHAM</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the Citv manager of Messrs. Field's establishment—he trades as Cowan &amp; Co.—I don't know King's premises—I know him as an occasional customer—he came and asked if I would pur<lb></lb>chase some wax, and I sold him in return some night-lights—when I re<lb></lb>ceived the wax I sent it to the other establishment at Lambeth—on another day King brought me a bag with some broken pieces of wax, which is lying at Moorgate Street—Mr. Field saw the bag.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SLEIGH</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">BROOKWILL</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you say at the Police Court?"J believe Messrs. Johnson &amp; Co. must have purchased the wax through igno<lb></lb>rance; a good judge might be mistaken. <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did, but not respecting those persons.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-627" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-627" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-627" type="surname" value="KING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-627" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN KING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an oil and oolourman, of 153, Union Street, Borough—I sell to Messrs. Cowan &amp; Co., to Johnson &amp; Co., and Gregory's—I sold (Gregory's 2 cwt. of white wax and about 3 cwt. of yellow; to Edwards, the doll maker, 4 or 6 cwt., and to Johnson about 2 cwt—when Mr. Field called on me I had 2 cwt. of yellow wax in my possession, and some white wax besides; about 17 cwt. altogether—I got that from Jewell, the marine store dealer of the New Cut—he began to come to me about July, 1872, and continued till about a fortnight before Mr. Field came to me—he</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180194"></xptr>
               <p>brought it in a cart sometimes, and sometimes in a barrow—and up to November last, George Castle used to be with him in the cart, but he did not come in—Jewell came alone after that—I don't know Howe—I always gave 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for the yellow and 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for the white—I have the invoice here, and I think one shows that I gave a little more for the white—the yellow was as if it had been turned out of a basin, and the white was sometimes in blocks and sometimes in broken pieces—the white was gene<lb></lb>rally whole, but there may have been a broken piece now and then—I have not seen Jewell since this inquiry.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SLEIGH</hi>. I don't understand much about the wax trade—I don't think I understand enough to make a bargain—I don't know that Mr. Field has sworn that the wax found at my premises was worth over 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a pound—I kept the whole of it in my shop—I swear that—I small portion of it was found in my bedroom, which I removed in conse<lb></lb>quence of an alteration on my premises—that was only about 2 cwt.—I had in stock at that time, I think, 2 cwt., and likewise 2 cwt. of white in the warehouse—all the rest was in the bedroom—the transactions began before November, 1872—I have been to Jewell's shop—he deals in rags and bones, and metal—I sold that wax to Gregory's at 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a pound—I paid 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for it—he had an invoice either from me or my son, with my name and address on it—I asked Jewell where he got the wax—I thought it a funny thing that a rag and bone dealer should be dealing in wax—he said he had it from a firm who had an account with a wax house—that was sufficient information for me, and I bought with confidence.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. M. WILLIAMS</hi>. I thought I was giving a fair price for it—it is on my invoice—I am in a large way of business—I do about 9,000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a year—I was satisfied with Jewell's representation—I had known him sometime, and knew his father-in-law, Mr. Davis, of London Road—I did not think it extraordinary that he should be dealing in wax—I deal in wax—I did not know that it was in an unfinished state when I bought it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> Seventeen hundredweight in five or six months is not 8 large dealing for an oil and colour man—I should be satisfied to buy double the quantity—I hear that Jewell has got out of the way—I only know it from hearsay; I have not taken any trouble to inquire.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-628" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-628" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-628" type="surname" value="JOHNSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-628" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE JOHNSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a candle-maker, of 175, Bishopsgate Street Without—I received about half a dozen blocks of yellow wax from Mr. King in exchange for candles.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. M. WILLIAMS</hi>. The bargain was at 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 9<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. per lb., but it was not paid for—I believe it to be a fair price—I chiefly trade in tallow, but I buy wax—I do not know much about it, or whether it was in an unfinished state.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-629" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-629" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-629" type="surname" value="EDWARDS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-629" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN EDWARDS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a wax-doll manufacturer, of Waterloo Road—I bought wax of Mr. King, and showed a sample of it to Mr. Field.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. M. WILLIAMS</hi>. I paid 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. or 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. per lb. for it, and I gave a fair price for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> I have bought wax from Mr. Field, and have given him more, but not for the same sort of wax.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-630" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-630" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-630" type="surname" value="RUMBLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-630" type="given" value="JOHN WILLIAM"></interp>JOHN WILLIAM RUMBLE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a painter—I know George Castle and Jewell—was in Mrs. Castle's service several times, on and off, to Christmas last—she and George Castle were together at that time—they kept a rag and metal shop—George Castle managed it chiefly, but his mother attended</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180195"></xptr>
               <p>to the shop—I have seen wax there a great many times—the last time was in September—the yellow wax was in the shape of a basin, and the white in cakes about the size of this book, but broken—I have seen Ralph; bring it in a truck or barrow, and under his coat, more than once—George Castle received it from him, and I have seen him put it into the scale, and his mother sent out the money to Ralph—I used to go out in a cart with Ralph on a Saturday, and I have put yellow and white wax into the cart at his direc<lb></lb>tion—we went with it first to Suffolk Street, Whitechapel, to a shop belong<lb></lb>ing to Mrs. Castle, and from there we went to Howe's, in Cambridge Heath Road, and took some metal from the other shop, and George Castle got out of the cart and had some talk with Howe, and then came and asked me to give him the wax, and it was taken into Howe's shop, and left there—it was white and yellow wax mixed, about, three-quarters of a cwt.—on one occasion we took wax there, George Castle said he would not leave it, because How he had not paid for the hut lot—it was brought back, and I think it was left with a man named Page—I have seen wax delivered at Howe's two or three times, about 3 or 4 cwt. on each occasion—I had also been in the cart with Castle to Jewell's shop, when wax was taken in a sack, yellow and white; that has happened several times, but I had never been in the shop.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. W. SLEIGH</hi>. I have had no money from the police, but Sergeant Croome has sent me 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. twice for my trouble in coming to the Court, and I have had; 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. from Brockweli, not more—I have not had 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. from him—he has not been paying all the witnesses—I have got into employment since this case began, with Mr. Purchas, of Wood Street, Golden Square—I got that for myself—I did not get a character; we don't require one in our line—I have been convicted of buying a ticket of a watch of a man who is doing seven years, but of nothing else—I got nine months—the police asked me to give them information as to who was buying this property, and I mentioned Ralph, and Castle, and Jewell—I did not mention King—I did not know that wax had been bought in large quantities by King, Edwards, Johnson, and others—I told the police that How was a receiver on the same night I spoke about Castle—I know Noble &amp; Ross now—I never worked there in my life—I did not know from. Castle that Johnson and King bought largely—I saw Ralph at Castle's three times—I have no recollection of having said "I cannot swear whether or not I have seen Ralph at Mrs. Castle's three times"—I will not swear I did not—I said he had brought wax under his coat in a handkerchief—I cannot tell you the date—I did not; think it extraordinary—I mentioned, that before I heard of the reward—I have sworn that I should not mind receiving the reward of 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and that I did not say anything about it before I heard of the reward—I was then asked if I had told the police about it—It did not say I would not have the reward if it was offered me—I should like to have it now—I did not tell the Magistrate that I did not know the name of my employer—Mr. Lewis asked me to spell it; I could not do so till I looked at the paper—the name is Mitchener—I offered as an excuse that I had only been there a few days, and that I had a bad memory—I won't swear I did not say "I refused what was offered me"—I don't remember refusing anything—I came forward to assist the ends of justice—the matter about the ticket of a watch was eight or ten years ago—it was in Oakley Street, Lambeth—I am sure it was six or seven years ago—I was tried at the Surrey Sessions for receiving a stolen watch, the property of Mr. Moore, for whose father I. worked—I was never charged with stabbing my father</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180196"></xptr>
               <p>four weeks ago, or my brother; there is no truth in it—two policemen did not come to my house to look after me and take me, nor did I run away without my coat—there is no truth in the suggestion.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CROOM</hi>. I went into Mrs. Castle's service nine or ten years ago, but I had never been regularly in her service.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Ralph</hi>, I have never been in Mrs. Castle's shop. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi>, I am certain of you—I was shown a number of men and picked you out.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> Mrs. Castle knew I was convicted—I was working for her at the time, and I went back there to work, and stayed there off and on for some years—she did not reproach me with my character then.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-631" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-631" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-631" type="surname" value="DENNIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-631" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH DENNIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Walter Dennis, of 44, Carlisle Street, Lambeth—I know Ralph by sight; he lives in the same Court opposite me, and Mrs. Scott lives in the same house with him—I have worked for Mrs. Castle several years at rag and paper sorting and house cleaning—I have seen Mrs. Scott come there from the end of September, or the beginning of October, till three weeks afterwards—she generally came every morning at 9 or 10 o'clock, and brought a large bundle under her shawl and went away without it—Mrs. Castle has been in the house at the time, and sometimes her son and son's wife—after Mrs. Scott left I have seen white and yellow wax on the floor, in the shape of basins—I saw that every time she came—when she came in I used to go out in the yard to do my work, and sometimes I was Bent for to get change, which I brought and gave to Mrs. Castle—I did net see what she did with it—my mother, Mrs. Cook, sometimes went there to work—our court is not five minutes' walk from Mr. Field's factory—Mrs. Castle sometimes told me to fetch her son while Mrs. Scott was there, and he came—I have seen Ralph, and Mrs. Scott, and George Castle, several times drinking together at the Carlisle Arms, which is not far from the factory—I went there to fetch beer—I saw Jewell there once with George Castle and Ralph—on 14th December George Castle told me to go to Jewell's house, and I went there and assisted them, and saw Ralph drive up to Jewell's door in a cart, which I believe was George Castle's—they brought something in a bag to Jewell's shop, and after they had gone I saw some large pieces of white wax in the parlour—once when I was working at Mrs. Castle's, George Castle gave me a bag, and asked me if I would take it to Jewell's for him—on my way I fell down—I then went into my own house and sat down, and the top of the bag came open, and I saw pieces of yellow wax in it—my sister-in<lb></lb>law and my mother were there, and saw it—that was in November—I took it to Jewell's, and saw Mrs. Jewell; Mr. Jewell was not up—shortly after dinner, in consequence of something my mother' said, I went to Mrs. Castle's, and told George Castle that a gentleman had been to my mother, and asked her if she was aware that Mrs. Castle bought, white wax and scented soap—he said "I have heard a different thing altogether"—Mrs. Castle came in and said "<hi rend="italic">Liz</hi>, what is that?"—I asked her whether she was aware that the gentleman came and asked that—she said it was no such thing; that Castle used to try, but they did not now—I did not see the gentleman—I said it was nothing to do with me, but they must take warning—I went home and told my mother to come—I left off going' to Castle's on the Saturday after I left—I still saw Mrs. Scott going out of the house every morning with a bundle under her arm, not going towards Mrs. Castle's, but in a direction that would lead her to Jewell's, which is a quarter of an hour's walk—when she returned she had no bundle—Mrs. Castle's is ten minutes'</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180197"></xptr>
               <p>walk from my place—before Mrs. Castle was taken, in consequence of some<lb></lb>thing that was said to me, I went to Cookson's house; my mother and my husband went with me—when I got there I saw Mrs. Castle and her daughter—she said "Oh, <hi rend="italic">Liz</hi>! you have done for me, nobody has been taken till to-night; Rumble has <hi rend="italic">rounded</hi>"—I said I had seen the wax there, and told her what I had said to Mr. Field—she said "<hi rend="italic">Oh, Liz</hi>! you have done for me and my boy; all you have said to-night you can deny in the morning; take care what you say for my son George and me"—Sergeant Croome then came in and took her in custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. M. WILLIAMS</hi>. I have been told that if I gave evidence I should be well paid for it—this was just after I had told about the wax—I think it was Sergeant Croome who said so—I have been convicted twice, once for striking a person with a poker, and once for receiving a stolen jacket—I got one month for that—after that I had six months' for taking lodgings in a false name—it was not for robbing my lodgings, they were un<lb></lb>furnished—that was at Stone's End, Borough, and I think it was last July three years—my landlord prosecuted me, and I served the four months—I have received 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. from Mr. Brockwell, and 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. was given to my husband—I have not had 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., nor have my family—Mrs. Cook is my mother—I have had 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week, but not from Mr. Brockwell; it was given me by a gentleman at Mr. Field's; Croome has given me nothing—he gave my husband 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. when Mrs. Castle was taken.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CROOME</hi>. I worked some time for Mrs. Castle; some<lb></lb>times in the yard and sometimes in the house—I took particular notice of Mrs. Scott, because people in the neighbourhood used to talk about her taking bundles out—I did not take notice of any other customer, because no other customer used to come into the parlour—I used to do the house cleaning, and when she came I was always in the parlour—I was there from 8 in the morning till 7 at night—I saw her there on the Monday or Tuesday in the week I left, but not in the latter part of the week—I. was first asked about this the end of April, after I left—I had not talked it over in the meanwhile, and my attention bad not been drawn to it—I don't know that Mrs. Scott brought a number of bags for Mrs. Castle in the bundle, as she finished them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LYON</hi>. I don't know that Mrs. Scott took in washing—I have not seen babies' petticoats hanging outside Mrs. Castle's door—Mrs. Scott used to take a bundle under one arm, and a basket on the other to Mrs. Castle's—I have known her three or four years, but never knew her to take in washing—she did wash for my mother three years ago, but not lately—I don't know that she washed for Mrs. Bitham, of the Carlisle Arms, for four year.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> Mrs. Castle knew I had been convicted, and used to send for me afterwards—I had to <hi rend="italic">go</hi> several times to the Police Court, and lost my work, and have had none since.</p>
