                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-633" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-633" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-633" type="surname" value="CROOME"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-633" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN CROOME</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a detective-serjeant of Scotlaud Yard—I was first instructed in April—I accompanied Mr. Field on his first visit to King's, and from there we went to Jewell's, where I heard a conversation between Mr. Field and Jewell—after leaving Jewell's we went to Castle's and had some conversation with George Castle—Mr. Field gave him the opportunity to find out the person he spoke of, and he promised to come and see Mr. Field on the 15th April—I never saw him again till I took him in custody at Paddington on 3rd June—I told him in the passage that I had been</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180201"></xptr>
               <p>looking for him some time and should take him in custody—he said "Well, don't make a noise, there are people here"—we went into the parlour, and the females went out—I told him the charge and he said "Have you got Jewell"—I said "No, not yet"—he said "He knows as much about it as I do"—I took him to the station—I had been to his mother's shop for him, and also to the house where he lived, but could not find him—on 30th April I took Mrs. Castle at her son's house—Mrs. Dennis was present, and Mrs. Cook, and Mrs. Dennis's husband, the son-in-law—I told her the charge—she said "I know nothing about it"—I said that Mrs. Scott had been seen on several occasions going to her house with a bag—she said she did not know Mrs. Scott, and asked me to let her stay till the morning—I said No, I had already been to her house, and was told she was out—I took her to the station—on 24th April I went to Howe's premises, under instruc<lb></lb>tions from Mr. Field, and purchased of Howe 10 lbs. of wax, 7 lbs of which was afterwards identified—I said I wanted half a cwt. or more—he said he could not supply me then, but no doubt he could get it—I paid him 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for the 10 lbs., but it was weighed as only 7 lbs.—I called again on the 28th, I told him he had made a mistake, and charged only 7 lbs.—instead of 10 lbs., and gave him 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. more, making 16<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he had told me on the first occasion that he could not tell of whom he bought the wax, and he took down a file and searched, and produced a printed bill with the heading torn off, and said "This is the receipt," but I found it referred to oil—on the second occasion, 30th April, he produced a bill with the name of Hayward on it, but no address, and told me he had asked for the man's address, but he would not give it him—I asked him if he knew a man named Castle—he said "No"—we both asked him if he had given samples to a man named Addis, in the employ of Mr. Williams, 108, Minories, to sell 2 cwt. of wax—he said "No, I don't know the man, and have never given samples of wax to anyone to sell"—I took Howe in cus<lb></lb>tody on 8th May at his house, and told him it was for receiving some wax—he said "I did not receive it, I bought it of the man I told you, Hayward, a traveller"—I took Ralph on 30th April, and told him the charge was stealing large quantities of Mr. Field's wax—he said "1 know nothing about it, very well, I will go"—on the night of June 6th, I took Witham at a public-house in Suffolk Street, Mile End, and told him the charge—he said "I did not receive it, what I have shown and tried to sell to Mr. Steer of Lambeth Walk, and Mr. Hall of the Cut, and another person, was given me to sell by George Castle"—he did not mention the third name, but he described the shop in Union Street, Borough, and said "If you lock me up I shall tell the Magistrate all I know; I don't see why I should suffer for other people; I hope Mr. Field will not discharge a number of innocent men, as there are only two or three more in it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WARNER SLEIGH</hi>. I gave Howe no intimation on the first occasion that I was a detective; he did not know it till the second occasion—I did not find out the mistake in the charge for the wax till I went home—it was got out by Mrs. Howe, and when I said that I wanted some more, she fetched her husband from the parlour—I gave a sovereign, I think, and the change was given me in silver—if Howe had been candid, and told me where he bought it, Mr. Field would not have charged him—he said on the first occasion that he would get a receipt for the wax from the traveller who came every Thursday, and on the second occasion he voluntarily produced the receipt—I have never given Mrs. Dennis anything</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180202"></xptr>
               <p>she was putting her boots on—she then took the wax away, and re<lb></lb>turned without it—soon after Christmas a man come and asked me if I was aware that Mrs. Castle bought white or yellow wax, or scented soap—I said "No," and told my daughter, who was working at Castle's at the time—she went there next day and returned, and in consequence of what she said I went there and saw George Castle and his mother—I said the gentleman asked me if I was aware whether they bought white or yellow wax, or scented soap, and that I had said "No"—she said "I will tell you what Mrs. Scott brought; it was a few candles, and a little soap, and I could as well send you to Mr. Field's for it as her"—young Mrs. Castle said that they had a different story to that, for someone passed and heard the conversation, and it was said some one used to buy it who did not buy it now—I told my daughter's hus<lb></lb>band of this, and she left in consequence at the end of the week—I was present when Mrs. Castle was apprehended at her son-in-law, Cook<lb></lb>son's house—she said to my daughter, "<hi rend="italic">Liz</hi>, if you have said anything, you have done for me and my boy, but never mind, you can deny all you said to-morrow morning"—my daughter had told her that she had been to Mr. Field's—the police then came, and nothing more was said.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LYON</hi>. Mrs. Scott went out sometimes at 10 o'clock, and sometimes a little after—I only went out to work once or twice a week, sometimes at 8 o'clock, sometimes at 10 o'clock, and sometimes at 2 o'clock, just as people wanted me—I only saw Mrs. Scott at Castle's twice, both times on Saturdays—Mrs. Scott has never done anything for me, nor" do I know that she took in washing, but she did a little for me, at her own house, two years ago, when I took in washing—I have not seen her go out with a basket—I do not know that she made babies' frocks and petticoats—I never saw any outside her door—I never bought one of her—what I said at the Police Court was that I bought one of Mrs. Castle—when Mrs. Castle was taken, I did not say "Thank God! I know nothing about it," or "Thank God, they cannot touch me."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LEWIS</hi>. Mrs. Cookson has three babies—one of them was not dying at that time—my daughter has only been convicted twice, not three times—I did not say "Mrs. Cookson, this is your doing, and now I will make it hot for your mother."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> My daughter was employed at Mrs. Castle's at the time she was convicted, and she worked for her afterwards—I did not know that Mrs. Scott was a laundress, or that she washed for the Carlisle public-house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-634" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-634" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-634" type="surname" value="DENNIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-634" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH DENNIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the sister-in-law of the other Elizabeth Dennis—I was at Mrs. Cookson's house when Mrs. Dennis came in—she had a little white bag with her—I looked at it, and saw three pieces of yellow wax, in the shape of a basin—she said she was going to take it to Jewell's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-635" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-635" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-635" type="surname" value="FRANCES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-635" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN FRANCES</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Alfred Frances, of 48, Union Street, thirteen doors from Mrs. Castle's, in the same street—Mrs. Scott came into my shop last August—as a rule she generally carried something under her shawl, in this way—I may take an oath that I have seen her do so four times a week—she generally bought something when she came, and she generally told me she was going to Mrs. Castle's, and would call for it as she came back—she was away sometimes half an hour, or it might be an hour—sometimes she paid beforehand, but generally afterwards—she never had any bundle under her shawl when she came back—on the Saturday</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180203"></xptr>
               <p>after Christmas she came in with Ralph and another man, who I do not know, and Scott said to Ralph "Come along, let us be going now;" and she said that they wanted to see Maggie—that is George Castle's wife—she said that she would call as she came back—she did not do so, but the other man came, not Ralph—she had told me previously that Maggie had been barmaid at the Carlisle Arms—that is near Mr. Field's factory—she came in on the day of the University Boat Race, and bought a small tin sauce<lb></lb>pan and a small vase, and left them till she came back—when she came back she had something under her shawl—she generally came four times a week, an I generally bought something: shirts, chemises, drawers, and articles of all descriptions—I did not notice on what days she came—I have sworn to four days positively, but she was in the habit of coming in regularly every day—I was quite as positive at the Police Court as I am now—she carried a bundle after Christmas, the same as before—at times she bought nothing, but only came in to have a little conversation—when she made a purchase she made a bundle, and carried it on top of a small bag or basket—I did not say at the Police Court that the things she bought of me she sometimes put under her shawl—my deposition was read over to me, and I signed <hi rend="italic">it</hi>—I do not believe I ever said it—I have been in the habit of dealing with the prosecutor's firm—I first spoke to the man I take the paper from about giving evidence—before that I had no idea whatever of giving evidence.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I did not buy soap and candles of the prosecutor, only waste-paper—when Mrs. Castle has come to my place I have seen some thing under her shawl, but I have not known what it was—George Castle's house is thirteen houses distant from my shop—I did not know that she was a laundry-woman—I should have put things under my shawl as she did, I have no doubt.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-636" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-636" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-636" type="surname" value="SIMONS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-636" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MARY SIMONS</persName>
                  </hi>. I know the Castles—I went to their house last year, but not to buy anything—I saw a cart standing outside, and things were being put into it—the horse's head was towards Lambeth Walk—Mrs. Castle was inside the shop, and her son, too—I saw some parcels on the counter, and an ordinary carpet bag, such as a gentleman might travel with—one parcel that was in the bag fell over, and I saw that it contained white wax, some of it escaped on to the counter—this was more than a year ago.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-637" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-637" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-637" type="surname" value="SIMONS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-637" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES SIMONS</persName>
                  </hi>. I know the Castles—about three months ago I met George Castle in a horse and cart, he stopped under the tail of the cart, and took out two large cakes of white wax and one of brown—they were in the shape of a bowl—he took them into his shop.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-638" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-638" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-638" type="surname" value="SUNDELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-638" type="given" value="SEYMOUR"></interp>SEYMOUR SUNDELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a glass shade and wax flower maker, at 51, Lower Marsh—I have known the woman Scott—about three months ago I bought some wooden cases of her; I noticed a little wax about the mouths of the cases—she afterwards came and asked if I was disposed to buy wax—she brought about 10 lbs. as a sample, she said they mixed it themselves—and so they could sell it cheaper than anyone else—it was white wax—she asked me 18<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a lb.—from, first to last I bought about 80 lbs. of her at 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 40<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I ultimately sold about 22 lbs, of it to Mr. Soames, the traveller to Mr. Field, the remainder was used for my home purposes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SLEIGH</hi>. My workman made it into wax flowers—I got 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. per lb. from Mr. Soames—I did not know of the robbery at that time—Mr. Field came to me about it—Mrs. Scott told me that her husband was a wax mixer—I went to her house about the wood I bought—I saw no</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180204"></xptr>
               <p>sign of wax mixing there—I never saw her husband—the wood was in a shed at the side of the house; it is a cottage—I got no receipt for the wax—I did not have it in one lot, but in seven or eight, as I wanted it—I did not enter it in my book.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-639" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-639" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-639" type="surname" value="SEXTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-639" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS SEXTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a furniture dealer, of 16; Great Charlotte Street, Blackfriars Road—I know Jewell and George Castle—on one occasion I saw them together outside my shop—they had a horse and cart—Jewell showed me a piece of yellow wax, and I believe there was some white in the parcel—I went with them in the cart to several places for the purpose of selling it—there was about half or three-quarters of a cwt. in the cart, both yellow and white—we did not find a customer—I had known Jewell six or seven years—I had never known him dealing in wax before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LEWIS</hi>. The wax that I saw in the cart was exceedingly dirty.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-640" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-640" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-640" type="surname" value="VAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-640" type="given" value="JAMES BE"></interp>JAMES BE VAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a chairmaker, of 12, Great Charlotte Street, Blackfriars Road—in consequence of what Sexton said to me, I went out and found a cart, and George Castle with it—at the bottom of the cart there was a large quantity of yellow and white wax of different shapes; some were basin-shaped, and some in thin pieces, some entire and some broken—Sexton asked me, in George Castle's presence, if I would buy it—I use wax in my trade—I understood they wanted about 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a lb. for it—I think the lump price was to be 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for all that was in the cart—I said I did not want any myself, but I went round with them to about twelve other chair makers—I 5<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a lb. was asked—we could not find a customer—we then went to George Castle's premises, in Union Street, and from there to Jewell's, in Gibson Street—Jewell asked George Castle "How do you get on?"—they spoke on one side—I could not hear what they said after that—we then went in the cart to Sexton's place 0—I said to Jewell, in George Castle's presenoe, "Have you been opposite?" that was to Bawn's, the chairmaker's—he said "Yes"—I asked if he had been to Edwards's, the doll-makers—George Castle said he had been there a long while ago—I said, if I had a customer at a future time would he have any more—he said "Plenty"—I have known Jewell two or three years as a neighbour, but not to speak to him—I had never known him dealing in wax.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LEWIS</hi>. Some of the wax was very dirty—I said I did not care about having anything to do with it for my own business—some of it was in small pieces, and some larger—it had the appearance of old wax—I was not to get any benefit out of it—I went with them as much for a ride as anything else—perhaps I might have had something if it had been sold, but I was not offered anything.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SLEIGH</hi>. The Castles were not known to me—Mr. Sexton asked me about it—travellers come round with wax and all sorts of things to sell—we deal at a certain place, and have done for years.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-641" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-641" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-641" type="surname" value="BOOTH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-641" type="given" value="WILLIAM JAMES"></interp>WILLIAM JAMES BOOTH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am eleven years old—I life at 3, College Place—Mrs. Scott lives in the same court—she gave my mother a cat—just after Christmas I went to Mrs. Scott's garden to look for it—I found it under the straw in a shed—I saw some wooden boxes there covered over with straw, and on the ground I saw three pieces of white wax—I dropped one of them, it was a three cornered piece—it broke into three little pieces—I took it home to my grandmother—I saw Mrs. Scott go out at 8 o'clock one morning, with a parcel under her shawl.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LYON</hi>. I found my cat in the shed under the straw,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180205"></xptr>
               <p>playing with the kitten—I did not not lift up much of the straw—the wax was rather dirty.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-642" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-642" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-642" type="surname" value="MAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-642" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE MAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a chair-maker—I know Mrs. Castle; not much of her son—about ten months ago she came to my shop—I was not at home, I saw her afterwards—she left some wax, about 12 lbs.—it was of a reddish cast—she asked me 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 1lb. for it—I did not take it because I can buy it 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a lb. or 2 oz. at a time for that.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LEWIS</hi>. I thought she asked too much, and I do not use above a quarter of a pound a week, and that would have lasted me a twelvemonth.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-643" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-643" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-643" type="surname" value="ADDIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-643" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY ADDIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the employ of Williams &amp; Co., 108, Minories—the prisoner Howe has been known to me some little time; he has an oil and colour man's business in Cambridge Heath Road—I have been in the habit of using the Three Colts public-house, a short distance from his house—I had a conversation with his brother about some wax, and afterwards with him—he handed me two pieces of wax, one dark and one light—he said he should have about 2 cwt. of it; this was given me as a sample—he said he wanted a quarter of a pound—I showed the sample to Palmer, and also to Mr. Williams, my employer—I afterwards saw Howe, and told him they would buy half a cwt. at Mr. Williams's, and a cwt. at Mr. Gadsden's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SLEIGH</hi>. I have been in Mr. Williams's employ two and a half years—I was in respectable employment before then—I have known Howe some years; he has borne an excellent character during that time—I have not been paid 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a day for my expenses; I had 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. the first day, and a half-crown for a cab home—it was Howe's brother that showed me the samples, not Howe himself—I said at first that it was Howe; but, on considering, I found it was his brother—he gave me the samples in his presence—he went and fetched them from his premises; they are the same premises as the prisoner's—he is a wholesale, as well as a retail, oil and colourman—he keeps a man on the premises to mix wax—after I saw Mr. Field about this, I told Howe that I had heard the wax was stolen, and he had better not have anything to do with it—he said he should not buy any mure of it, and he was much obliged to me for telling him of it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> The shop is Howe's, I believe—the brother fetched the samples from the shop, and brought them to me at the public-house and asked if I could-sell them—I said "Yes"—both the brothers were at the public-house—I saw them afterwards several times, both in the shop toge<lb></lb>ther—the prisoner sometimes took part in the conversation—this was about Whitsuntide, I think; about the middle of April.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-644" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-644" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-644" type="surname" value="MIDDLETON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-644" type="given" value="EDWIN"></interp>EDWIN MIDDLETON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am with my brother, an oil and colourman, in George Street, St. George's-in—the East—I have known Howe personally about twelve months—I have done business with him about two years—in August last year I bought 104 lbs. of wax of him at 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a lb., with some oil and cans—this is the invoice—the amount is 23<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—on one occa<lb></lb>sion I went to his premises in Cambridge Heath Road, to the back of the shop, and there saw some pieces of yellow wax—there was also a transaction in April, 1 cwt. 2 qrs. 6 lbs., at 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a lb.—a portion of the wax I bought of Howe was afterwards shown to Mr. Field and his foreman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SLEIGH</hi>. I have known Howe for two years as a respectable tradesman—I have never heard a blemish on his character—some part of the wax we should not have paid so much for, as it was not</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180206"></xptr>
               <p>genuine wax—sometimes we buy from samples of travellers who come round—<hi rend="italic">Howe</hi> give us these receipts at the time—everything was done in a per<lb></lb>fectly business-like manner.</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">Re-examined</hi>) When travellers come round they give the names and addresses of their principals.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-645" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-645" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-645" type="surname" value="WALKER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-645" type="given" value="EDWIN"></interp>EDWIN WALKER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am manager to Messrs. Field, at the Star Night Light Works—I have known Witham in the neighbourhood of those works for some years—after the apprehension of Ralph and Mrs. Castle, I met Witham in Union Street—he said "What do you want with me?"—I said I thought he could give some information relative to the robbery of the wax from Mr. Field's—he said "Yes, I can, I know all about it; I bought three-quarters of a cwt. some odd pounds in Castle's shop myself'—I asked him if he would come and tell Mr. Field—he said "No, I do not want to see Mr. Field, but I shall be at the Court next hearing, and I will tell the Magistrate the same as I have told you"—next evening I met him at the same place, and I then told him that I found he had offered wax for sale—he at first said "I—No"—I said "It is no use for you to deny it, because I can tell you to whom you offered it"—he asked me who—I said to Mr. Hall's assistant, and also to Mr. Steane"—he said "Well, yes, I did," and he said he would tell that to the Magistrate—I again asked him if he would go to Mr. Field—he said No, ho would be at the Court next day, and he would tell the Magistrate the same as he told mo—I saw nothing more of him till Whit-Tuesday, when he came to me at the works in Paradise Street—he asked if I wanted to see him—I said "No, but if you have anything to say to me, I am quite ready to hear it"—he asked if I was not going to treat him—I said "Yes, you may have what you like"—we went together to the Bell public-house in Church Street, and he had half a quartern of gin—I left the house for a few minutes, and when I came back he had gone to the Crown—I called him out; he was not perfectly sober; and in a rambling manner he said he would tell Mr. Field that the man whom he discharged knew nothing about the robbery; that the right man was locked up, and two other men were at liberty—I then took him to Mr. Field, and after a conversion with him, I followed him out—he stopped and told me he could not say anything unless I locked him up; situated as he was he could not say a word out there, because if he did, he should never get another day's work among this class of people.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LYON</hi>. I mentioned that at the Police Court—a lad named William Maunder, a nephew of mine, first brought him to me—I sent him for him—when I first saw him in Union Street he went into the Dolphin public-house with one of the Castles—I did not give him any money on that occasion—I lent him a shilling the night I took him to Mr. Field—he said he had no money, and asked if I would give him a shilling—I said "No"—he said "Lend me a shilling"—I said "I will lend you one if you like, but I shall never get it again, I suppose"—that was understood I think.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-646" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-646" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-646" type="surname" value="DAVIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-646" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD DAVIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am warehouseman to Mr. Hall, an oilman in Lambeth Road—I know Witham—about twelve months ago he came and offered me some wax for sale—he said he had about three-quarters of a cwt.—he left me a sample—I showed it to my employer, but none was bought—it was yellow wax—I have since seen the sample that he brought me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LYON</hi> He did not say who he was selling it for</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187308180207"></xptr>
               <p>—he said he was selling it for a party; he did not mention the name—I knew he was acquainted with the Castles.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-647" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-647" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-647" type="surname" value="STEANE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-647" type="given" value="FREDERICK GEORGE"></interp>FREDERICK GEORGE STEANE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an oil and colourman, 170, Lambeth Walk—in September last young Witham came and offered me some yellow wax for sale—he brought a sample first, and then a bag, about three-quarters of a cwt.—he asked 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. per lb. for it—he said he had bought it at a rummage sale of the South Western Railway—I asked him to show me a catalogue of the sale—he did not do so—I would not buy it, and he took it away.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LYON</hi>. It was what was known in the trade as Jamaica beeswax; it was not all yellow, but light and dark—the market value at that time was about eight guineas a cwt.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-648" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-648" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-648" type="surname" value="PEACOCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-648" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM PEACOCK</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Police Inspector L</hi>) I was on duty at Tower Street station on the morning of 7th June—at that time Witham was in custody in one of the cells—T visited him during the night and morning, and asked if he was all right—he said "Yes," and he wanted to make a statement to me about the matter he was in the cell for, and requested that it might be detailed to the Magistrate—he said "I know all about it; I had some of the wax given to me to sell; I offered it for sale to a foreman of Mr. Hall's, Lambeth Road; they refused to purchase it. I left a sample; that was returned to me. I was employed by Mr. George Castle, of Union Street, Lambeth Walk; in June last a man drove up in Union Street, with a horse and cart, in front of a paper shop, near Castle's house, with three lots of wax. I weighed one of them; it weighed three-quarters of a cwt I don't remember what the others weighed. Mr. Castle was present at the time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-649" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-649" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-649" type="surname" value="DALES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-649" type="given" value="SOLOMON"></interp>SOLOMON DALES</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman L</hi> 34), At 10 o'clock on the night of 1st May, I took Harriett Scott into custody—I told her she would be charged with others in stealing wax from Messrs. Field's, and that Ralph was at the station—she said Ralph was a lodger of hers; if he knew anything about the wax she did not.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18730818-name-650" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-650" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-650" type="surname" value="RUMBLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18730818-name-650" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM RUMBLE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">re-examined</hi>). I have sworn that I was not taken to the Police Court by two policemen; that was what I said, and that was what I meant—I was taken by one man—I was not charged at all; no charge was made; I was taken to the station and let go—I was summoned by a man named Enowles for an assault—it was all put on to me by the Castles—no charge was entered on the sheet; I can swear that.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Howe and the two Castles received good characters.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">RALPH</hi>—
<rs id="t18730818-565-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18730818-565-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18730818-565-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>
                     <hi rend="smallCaps">GUILTY</hi> 
                     <hi rend="italic">of stealing.</hi>
                  </rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">SCOTT, M. A. CASTLE, HOWE, GEORGE CASTLE</hi>, <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">WITHAM</hi>—
<rs id="t18730818-565-verdict-2" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18730818-565-verdict-2" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18730818-565-verdict-2" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>
                     <hi rend="smallCaps">GUILTY</hi> 
                  </rs> 
                  <rs id="t18730818-565-punishment-71" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18730818-565-punishment-71" type="punishmentCategory" value="noPunish"></interp>
